model_explanation: S1 says Bill only received bananas, but S2 says Bill also received grapes, which contradicts the exclusivity implied by the word "only."
S1 says Mary was the only one who received apples, but S2 says Ellen also received apples, contradicting that exclusivity.
S1 says Sue was the only person who got apples, but S2 says Tom also got apples, which contradicts the exclusivity.
S1 states Bill exclusively got grapes, and S2 is consistent with that by saying Bill didn’t get any other fruit like oranges.
if Bill only got apples (S1), then it’s logically entailed that he didn’t get bananas, as confirmed by S2.
S1 says Sue only got apples. That means no bananas were given to her, so S2 follows logically.
S1 talks about what was only given to Ellen, but S2 talks about what was not given to Tom, which is a separate statement that doesn’t contradict or confirm S1.
S1 says only Tom received apples, which entails that no one else, including Mary, received apples. Therefore, S2 is entailed by S1.
S1 says only Tom got apples, but S2 contradicts that by stating Bill got apples too.
if Sue was the only one who got bananas (S1), then it follows that Tom didn’t get any, so S2 matches that.
